Yes, you can report it as Low severity.

Use wording like:

Title: Outdated Next.js Version 13.2.3 Detected

Severity: Low

Reason:
The application is running Next.js 13.2.3, which is affected by multiple public security advisories, including middleware authorization bypass issues. However, black-box PoC testing did not confirm unauthorized access, protected data exposure, SSRF, XSS, source map exposure, or cache poisoning.

Evidence:

Next.js 13.2.3 confirmed from public JS/runtime assets.

Build ID detected: iiZZTx3WpHSPqrvuGmFh1.

Protected routes such as /snap, /pwt, /data-platform redirected to login.

/_next/data/<buildid>/en/data-platform.json returned only login redirect metadata.

x-middleware-subrequest bypass attempts did not expose protected content.


Impact:
An outdated vulnerable framework version increases attack surface. If future routes or middleware logic depend only on vulnerable Next.js behavior, authorization bypass or other issues may become exploitable.

Recommendation:
Upgrade Next.js to a currently supported patched version. Also block external x-middleware-subrequest headers at the edge/proxy.

Do not report it as Critical unless you can show protected content/data is accessible without authentication.
